Cost model — databricks units, autoscaling, auto-termination.

Compute is the part of the platform you pay for by the second, so let's look at the three levers that control its cost.

The first lever is the rate by workload family. Compute is billed in databricks units, and the rate climbs as you go from jobs-light, to jobs compute, to sequel warehouse, to all-purpose, to serverless managed convenience. Picking the right family alone can change a workload's bill by two to three times.

The second lever, on classic compute, is spot versus on-demand workers. Spot machines are sixty to ninety percent cheaper, but they can be evicted at any time. So the rule is, the spark driver should always be on-demand, because losing it kills the whole job, while workers can mix spot and on-demand for E-T-L, where one or two evicted tasks are tolerable.

The third lever is autoscaling and auto-termination. Autoscaling adjusts worker count to load — set a realistic minimum and maximum. Too high a maximum wastes money on idle workers; too low and you throttle the job. Auto-termination is the single biggest cost control on all-purpose clusters — a thirty-minute idle timeout means a forgotten notebook costs at most thirty minutes of compute, not a whole weekend. Job clusters and serverless terminate automatically by design.
